<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06151235 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06151235 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; GIVE ME FIVE, MR. PRESIDENT -- A cadet,excited about receiving his diploma, gives a high-five Wednesday to PresidentBush during graduation at the Air Force Academy.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  US; PRESIDENT; WEAPON; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Egypt and the U.N. official in charge of nuclear disarmament today welcomedPresident Bush's proposal to stop the arms buildup in the Middle East byfreezing nuclear weapons and eventually banning all missiles.;    Japan alsopraised the plan, announced Wednesday by Bush. But China was wary and said itwas studying the proposal.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  BUSH ARMS PLAN GETS GOOD REVIEWSSO FAR, ONLY CHINA SHOWS CAUTIOUSNESS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     President Francois Mitterrand of France announced that his country has itsown global disarmament plan and was showing it to other permanent members ofthe U.N. Security Council today.;    The permanent members -- the UnitedStates, France, Britain, China and the Soviet Union -- also are the world'slargest arms suppliers.;    Mitterrand said the French plan was&quot;complementary&quot; to the U.S. proposal and would be made public Friday.;    Bushinvited all five nations to meet quickly with U.S. officials to work out a newcode for arms sales and transfers throughout the Middle East.;    His proposedrestraints on nuclear arms and materials would mainly affect Israel. TheJewish state is believed to be the only Middle East nation with a developednuclear-weapons capability, although it routinely declines to comment onreports about it.;    Israel welcomed Bush's plan Wednesday but said it wouldlike to see more emphasis on curbing conventional weapons.;    Israel favorsmore curbs on conventional weapons because Arab nations maintain a militaryadvantage in conventional forces of tanks, artillery and troops.;    Arabstates, however, want arms control programs to zero in on non-conventionalarms because of Israel's reported possession of nuclear weapons.;    In astatement to reporters today, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa welcomedBush's plan and said his nation hoped that &quot;all countries in the region willcommit themselves&quot; to doing away with weapons of mass destruction. This wasclearly a reference to Israel.;    For more than a decade, Egypt has receivedthe bulk of its arms from the United States. Other weapons suppliers includeFrance, Britain and China.;    The U.N. official in charge of disarmamentissues, Yasushi Akashi, said in Tokyo that the Bush plan would &quot;create moreauspicious conditions for the reduction of tensions&quot; and a stronger foundationfor international agreements, Kyodo News Service reported.;    Japan welcomedthe U.S. proposal, calling it &quot;a courageous action on this difficult issue.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910530  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  5A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  398  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday May 30, 199100151235,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>